HEADWORD: Pornography
<hw>Por*nog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a
harlot + <ets>-graphy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Licentious painting
or literature; especially, the painting anciently employed to decorate
the walls of rooms devoted to bacchanalian orgies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A treatise on prostitutes, or
prostitution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>obscene pictures, writings, drawings, motion
pictures, videos, or the like intended primarily to cause sexual arousal
and having little or no artistic merit; also, the content of such
materials.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Porosity</ent>⟦br⟧
